  "text": "where the mixing proportion n is small, F0 is the null distribution and F1 is the non-null or \"alternative\" distribution. Equivalently, for each 1 ≤ i ≤ n, one assumes that Xi has probability 1 − n of being a null case and probability n of being a non-null case. Let f0 and f1 denote the densities corresponding to null and non-null cases respectively. The marginal density is given by f (x) = (1− n)f0(x) + nf1(x). The mixture model (1) provides a powerful and convenient framework for large-scale inference and has been widely used in the literature [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ).",
